{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/extraordinary-data-visualisation-circular-chart-fe2d835ef929", "time": 1683010775.408266, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/extraordinary-data-visualisation-circular-chart-fe2d835ef929/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Extraordinary Data Visualisation \u2014 Circular Chart | by Christopher Tao | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Extraordinary Data Visualisation \u2014 Circular Chart", "description": "Draw a Circular Chart in Python Plotly. Data Visualisation shows the proportion, percentage and position relationships. Data Analyst, Data Scientist must know."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["It is very common to use a pie chart or a doughnut chart to represent the proportions of different components of the whole. However, recently I met such data visualisation requirements:", "Up to here, a pie chart or a doughnut chart still can be perfect options. However, pay attention to the rest of the requirements.", "Some cases need such requirements. For example, representing segments of DNA in terms of their similarity to a baseline.", "We can use a circular chart to visualise such relationships.", "As shown above, the circular chart consists of", "The data to be visualised is as follows.", "Here we got a 2-d array. Each sub-array represents a segment of the gene. The two numbers are the start point and the endpoint respectively.", "For example, the first gene [0.1, 0.25] means this gene segment start from 10% of the baseline and end up at 25%. Therefore, the length is 0.15 of the original.", "Now, let\u2019s see how to use Plotly to draw this circular chart.", "It is not too difficult to draw a circular chart using Plotly.", "Firstly, we need to import Plotly. If you haven\u2019t got the library, you can simply install it by pip install plotly.", "Plotly supports the polar coordinate system, which is perfect to be utilised to draw our circular chart. To draw a circle in a polar plane, the two important parameters are", "In our case, we need to use the radius r to distinguish our base circle and the other components (circle segments). The angle \u03b8 is important as we need it to show the start and the endpoint. In other words, we need 0\u2013360 degrees for the \u03b8 of the base circle, whereas the components depend on their corresponding proportions and positions.", "Let\u2019s define a function to get \u03b8.", "In this function, it takes two parameters. The first parameter pct is a list/tuple with two elements. The first element is the start percentage and the second element is the end percentage. The second parameter num_points indicates how many points we want to render on the plot for a full 360-degree circle. The more num_points the more smooth circle we will have. In my case, 360 points would be quite enough as human eyes will not be able to see the little angles.", "The num_points as I mentioned above, I would like to use 360 points. The r_gap means how much gap we want between the base circle and each segment.", "We also need to know what should be the radius of the chart to show all the segments inside. Since we have already known the r_gap. If we suppose the base circle has its radius 1, we can calculate the maximum radius we want.", "Now, let\u2019s initialise a figure using Plotly.", "Then, add the base circle. It should be coloured black. Here we define the radius r=1 so that the segment will be 1 + r_gap * (index + 1).", "Now, let\u2019s a little \u201cbar\u201d at the zero-degree to indicate where does the base circle start. Also, it can help to leave some space between the edge of the chart and the segments.", "Please be noticed that here we just need two points on the figure:", "Looks better now. Let\u2019s render our segments in a for-loop.", "OK. It looks like there is still something to do. As shown, there are several problems:", "Let\u2019s fix all the problems above-mentioned.", "Now, we have a perfect circular chart!", "In this article, I\u2019ve shown how to use Plotly to draw a circular chart representing both the proportion and position relationships of data.", "All the code can be found in my Google Colab notebook:", "Although sometimes data visualisation libraries may not provide some figures and charts out-of-the-box, we can still easily draw whatever is in our mind using Python. Plotly is one of such amazing data visualisation libraries.", "If you feel my articles are helpful, please consider joining Medium Membership to support me and thousands of other writers! (Click the link above)", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ffe2d835ef929&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fextraordinary-data-visualisation-circular-chart-fe2d835ef929&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fextraordinary-data-visualisation-circular-chart-fe2d835ef929&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A